Title: Доска соревнования на ликвидацию прорыва
Author: Marshak, S. (Samuil), 1887-1964
Abstract: Soviet factory workers work hard to fulfill the first Five-Year Plan. The blacksmiths and foundry-workers are rewarded for their labor with fast planes and cars. They are contrasted with idlers who drink and waste time. The title of the poem refers to the "gap" between the Soviet Union and Western industrialized countries such as the United States. The first Five-Year Plan was intended to increase Soviet productivity so it would not lag behind other countries.
Subject: Work ethic—Soviet Union—Juvenile poetry
Labels: Poster, Illustration, Art,

Author: Barto, Agnii︠a︡, 1906-1981

Highlights the positive opportunities and quality of life available to Soviet workers through communism. Title: Knizhka-kino-seans o tom, kak pioner Gans Stachechnyĭ Komitet spas
Author: Kobrinet︠s︡, F.
Abstract: An amazing children's book by an unknown artist who may have disappeared in Stalin's purges as did the printer Mikhail Tomsky. It dates, like Immer Bereit, to a period of intense collaboration with German Communists. The Nazi swastika, like the pot-bellied capitalist, are both depicted as enemies of the workers. Hans, who alerts the strikers that the police are on the way, has to flee Berlin for Moscow, where he is acclaimed as a hero. (Presumably he was caught up short like his Comintern brethren by the Hitler-Stalin pact a few years later.) The illustrations are in frames intended to mimic celluloid, with instructions for constructing a cinematograph.
Subject: Detskai︠a︡ kommunisticheskai︠a︡ organizat︠s︡ii︠a︡ i︠u︡nykh pionerov imeni Lenina—Juvenile fiction

Title: Millionnyĭ Lenin
Author: Zilov, Lev
Abstract: Exciting story of two boys from Calcutta who participate in an uprising against the Raj and are forced to flee. Hearing of Lenin and the Revolution, they stow away travelling through Port Said, making friends with some sailors. In Constantinople (Istanbul) they witness a Communist demonstration. Back on the ship they are mistreated by the captain, which results in a mutiny by the sailors, who raise a red undershirt as a flag, arriving finally in the Soviet Union where they witness a parade before Lenin's tomb and adopt warm clothing and determined revolutionary expressions, while retaining their turbans. Closes with assurance that in spite of Lenin's recent death, this Land of Freedom will go on thanks to it millions of defenders.
Subject: Communism—Juvenile fiction
Labels: Poster, Font, Vintage advertisement, Advertising,

Author: Zilov, Lev
Abstract: Exciting story of two boys from Calcutta who participate in an uprising against the Raj and are forced to flee. Hearing of Lenin and the Revolution, they stow away travelling through Port Said, making friends with some sailors. In Constantinople (Istanbul) they witness a Communist demonstration. Back on the ship they are mistreated by the captain, which results in a mutiny by the sailors, who raise a red undershirt as a flag, arriving finally in the Soviet Union where they witness a parade before Lenin's tomb and adopt warm clothing and determined revolutionary expressions, while retaining their turbans. Closes with assurance that in spite of Lenin's recent death, this Land of Freedom will go on thanks to it millions of defenders.
Subject: Communism—Juvenile fiction
Labels: Text, Illustration,

Title: Bolʹshevik Tom
Author: Pavlovich, Nadezhda
Abstract: A Classic of Soviet propaganda for children. Taking the names from the Adventures of Tom Sawyer, Pavlovich reforms the naughty boy along Marxist lines. Aunt Polly ("Teti︠a︡ Polli") does not know what to do with mischievous Tom: he steals sweets, gives the cat a haircut, scrawls on the walls, and even gets into his aunt's make-up box. Not even a good whipping will teach him a lesson! But Tom reforms after he dreams of a glorious Bolshevik rally and joins the proletarian revolution.
Subject: Tom Sawyer—Adaptations
Labels: Poster, Text, Illustration, Font, Vintage advertisement, Fiction, Retro style, Art,

Not even a good whipping will teach him a lesson! But Tom reforms after he dreams of a glorious Bolshevik rally and joins the proletarian revolution.
Subject: Tom Sawyer—Adaptations

Aunt Polly ("Teti︠a︡ Polli") does not know what to do with mischievous Tom: he steals sweets, gives the cat a haircut, scrawls on the walls, and even gets into his aunt's make-up box. Not even a good whipping will teach him a lesson! But Tom reforms after he dreams of a glorious Bolshevik rally and joins the proletarian revolution.
Subject: Songs, Russian
Labels: Text, Paper, Document, Font, Paper product,

Title: Knizhka pro knizhki
Author: Marshak, S. (Samuil), 1887-1964
Abstract: A slovenly boy severely abuses the books in his household, leaving missing covers, torn pages, and other damage in such classics as The Brothers Grimm, Don Quixote, and Robinson Crusoe, among others. The books decide to escape, and flee en masse to the public library where they are greeted by a strong, stern, library catalog. They are repaired and put to bed to convalesce. When the boy discovers that all of his books are missing, he goes to the library to inquire about borrowing. The books recognize the boy, alert the library catalog, and - as the final illustration implies - fly off the shelves to chase or attack him.
Subject: Books and reading—Juvenile fiction
Labels: Poster, Illustration, Cartoon, Art, Fictional character, Visual arts, Font, Comic book, Graphic design,

Title: Pi︠a︡tiletka : risunki i maket
Author: Laptev, A. (Alekseĭ Mikhaĭlovich), 1905-1965
Abstract: A panorama celebrating the early efforts to fulfill Stalin's first Five Year Plan. The strip's upper side includes several maps showing those sites where notable gains had been made in electrification, factory-building, metallurgy, and collectivization. Each page of the strip's lower side has flaps on the upper and lower edges, identical to those of a harlequinade. The flaps when closed show the level of development in those same areas 1927-1928. When the reader turns up the flaps, they reveal a dramatic image of the progress made between 1932 and 1933.
Subject: Industrial management—Soviet Union
Labels: Label, Font, Poster, Vintage advertisement,

Title: Okti︠a︡brenok postrelenok
Author: Agnivt︠s︡ev, N. I︠A︡. (Nikolaĭ I︠A︡kovlevich), 1888-1932
Abstract: A little boy who prefers airplanes, tramways and the radio to fairy tales, uses copies of 'Pioneer' to silence some of the beloved characters of pre-Soviet juvenile literature including Ivan Tsarevich, Baba Yaga and the Little Humpbacked Horse. A lively attack on traditional Russian children's books.

Abstract: Illustration of workers with hammers marching alongside soldiers before red flag, followed by enemies: the Englishman, an imperialist clown "kolonial'naia Petrushka!" who manipulates a khan like a toy "kat igrushka"; generals; capitalists; Roosevelt; counter revolutionaries w/ swastika on banner, bandits and fascists "Chto bandity, chto fashisty", etc. ending with Young Pioneers marching w/ red flag with soldiers in background.
Subject: Vsesoi︠u︡znai︠a︡ pionerskai︠a︡ organizat︠s︡ii︠a︡ imeni V.I. Lenina—Juvenile
Labels: Cartoon, Text, Illustration, Art,

Title: 80,000 loshadeĭ
Author: Voinov, Vladimir Vasil'evich, 1878-1938
Abstract: A story in rhyme about the Volkhov Hydroelectric Plant, which is located approximately 76 miles (122 km) east of St. Petersburg on the Volkhov River. As the first hydroelectric plant in the Soviet Union, the plant figured prominently in Lenin's electrification plan for the country, as a key alternative energy source to coal. Construction of the plant began in 1918, and the plant opened in 1926. Title of this book (80,000 horses) refers to the amount of energy generated by the plant.
Subject: Illustrated children's books—Soviet Union
Labels: Poster, Text, Games, Font, Pattern,

Construction of the plant began in 1918, and the plant opened in 1926. Title of this book (80,000 horses) refers to the amount of energy generated by the plant.

Abstract: Poems about the development of heavy industry in the Soviet Union. For Little Octobrists (young children not yet old enough for the Young Pioneers). The rhymes help them celebrate and support workers in the fields and coal-mines, who are all contributing to the Five-Year Plan.
